From the results of 3.2, the dependence of (I0–I)/I0 on H2O2 concentration follows two equations in the concentration of 0–1 mM and 1–8 mM, respectively. Based on the linear response of BSPOTPE/BSA-AuNCs to H2O2, the ratiometric detection method can also be used for the detection of the H2O2-related oxidases activities and the substrates. Glucose can be converted to gluconic acid and simultaneous production H2O2 under GOx catalyzing. Therefore, by monitoring the generated H2O2, glucose can be detected. In this work, BSPOTPE/BSA-AuNCs were used for detecting glucose in the presence of GOx. Before the detection of glucose by GOx catalyzing, the effect of GOx and glucose (without GOx) on the BSPOTPE/BSA-AuNCs probe was investigated (Fig. S2). The results indicate that GOx or glucose has little effect on the BSPOTPE/BSA-AuNCs probe. As the normal range of glucose in healthy human serum is about 3.9–7.8 (2 h after food) mM or 3.9–6.2 mM (empty stomach) [2], 1–8 mM of glucose was studied to test the proposed method (Fig. 3
                        ). Fig. 3B shows that the fluorescence intensity change ratio (I0–I)/I0 increased linearly with the glucose concentration in the range 1–8 mM. The resulting linear equation was (I0–I)/I0 = 0.0757 [glucose] + 0.0102. The performance of the proposed method for glucose determination was compared with various method such as colorimetric, electrochemistry and fluorescence method (Table 1
                        ). It could be found that the linear range of the proposed method is 1–8 mM, which is much narrower than other methods. Considering the normal range of glucose in healthy human serum is about 3.9–7.8 (2 h after food) mM or 3.9–6.2 mM (empty stomach), our proposed method has an incomparable advantage for glucose detection in human serum.
